WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:14.680
Let's start by making sure we understand why we're writing code in the first place.

00:00:14.680 --> 00:00:17.719
What we're trying to do is data science through code.

00:00:17.719 --> 00:00:21.120
We're trying to answer questions and make predictions that are difficult to do manually,

00:00:21.120 --> 00:00:23.719
so we automate it in the code.

00:00:23.719 --> 00:00:28.540
Ideally we do so in a way that is reproducible and easily augmented and that facilitates

00:00:28.540 --> 00:00:32.700
collaboration and outcome distribution.

00:00:32.700 --> 00:00:36.299
And if we come up with some code that we think that would be useful to others, we can share

00:00:36.299 --> 00:00:42.380
that too if we do, if we write a package for it.

00:00:42.380 --> 00:00:44.939
So code is written in the service of analysis.

00:00:44.939 --> 00:00:48.360
It's a means to an end, but it's also an artifact.

00:00:48.360 --> 00:00:49.619
This is really important.

00:00:49.619 --> 00:00:54.500
Your code is not temporary, at least not if you ever want to run it again.

00:00:54.500 --> 00:00:57.820
So we should not be treating it as an afterthought.

00:00:57.820 --> 00:01:00.980
It should be a primary concern because you are going to need to run it again someday

00:01:00.980 --> 00:01:04.620
and you need to trust that it will produce accurate results every single time you do

00:01:04.620 --> 00:01:08.580
run it.

00:01:08.580 --> 00:01:13.099
So since the code behind our analysis or prediction is important, we should know what we want

00:01:13.099 --> 00:01:14.660
out of it.

00:01:14.660 --> 00:01:20.540
Ideally we want reliability, the ability to depend on our code producing the correct results,

00:01:20.540 --> 00:01:24.860
and we want confidence that our functions won't break when new data comes in or that

00:01:24.940 --> 00:01:26.900
one area of the code won't break.

00:01:26.900 --> 00:01:31.019
If you make a change to one area of the code, it won't break another area of the code.

00:01:31.019 --> 00:01:35.500
We also want reproducibility so that you and others can run the same code with the same

00:01:35.500 --> 00:01:39.699
data and get the same results every single time.

00:01:39.699 --> 00:01:41.820
Flexibility goes hand in hand with extensibility.

00:01:41.820 --> 00:01:46.940
In many cases we want to be able to handle different data sets, inputs, context, things

00:01:46.940 --> 00:01:52.839
like that, and we need to be able to extend what we've already written to make incremental

00:01:52.839 --> 00:01:57.360
improvements to the code and in our projects.

00:01:57.360 --> 00:02:01.680
We want our projects to have longevity, to be relevant for the long term, and to accomplish

00:02:01.680 --> 00:02:05.199
this it has to be straightforward to update.

00:02:05.199 --> 00:02:09.039
We want to make it easy to iterate on the code since small changes over time are easier

00:02:09.039 --> 00:02:13.759
to absorb than a huge code drop in much the same way it's easier to put $20 away a week

00:02:13.759 --> 00:02:19.880
for a college fund rather than to find $1,000 at the end of the year to drop all at once.

00:02:19.880 --> 00:02:24.199
Finally we need the code to be scalable, flexible enough to handle more users, additional

00:02:24.199 --> 00:02:28.059
variables or inputs, and potentially larger data sets as well.

00:02:28.059 --> 00:02:32.800
So the overarching need here is to be able to trust the outcome of our analysis, which

00:02:32.800 --> 00:02:39.600
is directly related to the quality of the code that is producing the results.

00:02:39.600 --> 00:02:40.820
Code quality does matter.

00:02:40.820 --> 00:02:44.199
We should be examining it to make sure that it's up to snuff.

00:02:44.199 --> 00:02:45.199
How do we do that?

00:02:45.199 --> 00:02:51.000
Well, we can get some feedback during script execution in the form of console output, logs,

00:02:51.000 --> 00:02:54.720
errors, warnings and things like that when the code runs locally.

00:02:54.720 --> 00:02:58.360
And we also get user feedback from the people who are running the script or launching this

00:02:58.360 --> 00:03:00.080
shiny application.

00:03:00.080 --> 00:03:03.279
We could wait until it breaks in the field, but it's better to check it yourself before

00:03:03.279 --> 00:03:07.960
you release it to the rest of the world.

00:03:07.960 --> 00:03:12.360
The best way to do this is to create tests to verify the quality of the code.

00:03:12.360 --> 00:03:16.679
Just check the output of the script to make sure it's doing what it should.

00:03:16.679 --> 00:03:20.479
And test themselves, unit tests especially are separate R files that are designed to

00:03:20.479 --> 00:03:25.520
exercise the functional code to see how it handles various inputs and integration points.

00:03:25.520 --> 00:03:29.960
And by that I mean pieces of code that rely on the output of other pieces of code, like

00:03:29.960 --> 00:03:33.220
a function that relies on the output of another function.

00:03:33.220 --> 00:03:37.960
So you want to examine how quickly it runs as well and how well it runs under load to

00:03:37.960 --> 00:03:41.919
gauge its performance.

00:03:41.919 --> 00:03:46.639
One of the biggest benefits of testing is that you're able to make faster updates to

00:03:46.639 --> 00:03:50.960
your projects, because you run your tests if you run your tests after you make the changes,

00:03:50.960 --> 00:03:54.639
you'll get quick feedback on the impact of those changes.

00:03:54.639 --> 00:03:58.880
So the act of writing the test increases your visibility into internal dependencies, which

00:03:58.880 --> 00:04:01.720
are those integration points that I just mentioned.

00:04:01.720 --> 00:04:05.919
And you'll potentially gain a greater understanding of the meaning and the intent of the code,

00:04:05.919 --> 00:04:08.639
because you really need to understand the code extremely well in order to be able to

00:04:08.639 --> 00:04:13.399
test it effectively.

00:04:13.399 --> 00:04:16.519
Ideally when you write these tests, you're going to want to cover all of your code paths,

00:04:16.519 --> 00:04:19.880
but practically speaking, you're going to want to start with the major functions, inputs

00:04:19.880 --> 00:04:21.559
and integration points.

00:04:21.559 --> 00:04:24.519
You're not going to be able to test everything all at once, so focus on the parts that you

00:04:24.519 --> 00:04:29.160
think may be the most fragile.

00:04:29.160 --> 00:04:32.880
Once these tests are in place, you can then expand to other areas of the code once you've

00:04:32.880 --> 00:04:39.320
gotten sort of those major areas covered first.

00:04:39.320 --> 00:04:40.320
Manual testing.

00:04:40.320 --> 00:04:42.359
So you're going to do this as you're developing your code.

00:04:42.359 --> 00:04:44.880
You're going to run things in the console just to make sure things are working, there's

00:04:44.880 --> 00:04:48.679
spot checks, you want to make sure that the stuff that you're writing is actually producing

00:04:48.679 --> 00:04:50.600
the results you expect.

00:04:50.600 --> 00:04:54.040
The problem with those, though, I mean, they're very good, you want to run them, make sure

00:04:54.040 --> 00:04:57.399
things are working, but the problem is you're not going to remember what you ran three months

00:04:57.399 --> 00:04:59.920
later when you go to change the code.

00:04:59.920 --> 00:05:03.040
So it's really easy to have things break.

00:05:03.040 --> 00:05:05.640
Areas that used to work might break because you don't remember what tests you ran the

00:05:05.640 --> 00:05:09.320
first time to make sure that it was working in the first place.

00:05:09.320 --> 00:05:13.679
So to avoid this problem, you should convert some of those manual tests into a set of coded

00:05:13.679 --> 00:05:17.160
tests.

00:05:17.160 --> 00:05:21.000
Coded tests are called unit tests in this context because they exercise small units

00:05:21.000 --> 00:05:23.679
or pieces of a larger whole.

00:05:23.679 --> 00:05:26.559
And you'll want to run these often, again, because you're going to get feedback right

00:05:26.559 --> 00:05:29.200
away when you make changes.

00:05:29.239 --> 00:05:33.239
If you find an issue several weeks later after you've moved on to other things, tracking

00:05:33.239 --> 00:05:36.480
down the cause of that problem is really difficult.

00:05:36.480 --> 00:05:39.559
It's much better to build these in from the beginning if you can rather than to wrestle

00:05:39.559 --> 00:05:41.399
with a fallout later.

00:05:41.399 --> 00:05:45.880
So writing tests now rather than waiting for bugs to appear later is the classic case of

00:05:45.880 --> 00:05:50.119
an ounce of prevention being better than a pound of cure.

00:05:50.119 --> 00:05:53.119
So now that I've convinced you that writing unit tests is a good idea, let me show you

00:05:53.119 --> 00:05:56.119
how easy it is to get started.

00:05:56.119 --> 00:06:01.320
One of the most popular and useful packages for our code testing is test that.

00:06:01.320 --> 00:06:04.679
It's part of the tidyverse and it provides functions that make it easy to describe what

00:06:04.679 --> 00:06:10.200
you expect a function to do, including catching errors, warnings and messages.

00:06:10.200 --> 00:06:14.359
You can use the functions in test that to exercise any project, but here I'm going to

00:06:14.359 --> 00:06:17.760
give an example of test that on a package.

00:06:17.760 --> 00:06:20.440
To get it set up, it's three easy steps.

00:06:20.440 --> 00:06:23.160
You install the package test that.

00:06:23.160 --> 00:06:26.119
You also want to install use this, because we're going to use that package.

00:06:26.119 --> 00:06:30.720
It's a workflow management package that makes it easy to get going with projects.

00:06:30.720 --> 00:06:34.500
And in this case, it has a really nice function called use test that that sets up the infrastructure

00:06:34.500 --> 00:06:35.839
for your tests.

00:06:35.839 --> 00:06:40.679
And then to write the tests themselves, also when you use this, you use the use test function

00:06:40.679 --> 00:06:44.720
and that will create and open up your very first test file.

00:06:44.720 --> 00:06:47.440
So let's see how that looks.

00:06:47.440 --> 00:06:50.440
Can you see that okay?

00:06:50.440 --> 00:06:53.140
I'll try that.

00:06:53.140 --> 00:06:57.899
So here's a small demo package with three files that I have in here.

00:06:57.899 --> 00:06:58.899
Let's see.

00:06:58.899 --> 00:07:02.700
If I can make this a little bigger.

00:07:02.700 --> 00:07:03.700
It's small.

00:07:03.700 --> 00:07:05.059
There's only three files in here.

00:07:05.059 --> 00:07:07.140
Just a couple of functions in here.

00:07:07.140 --> 00:07:10.700
They're dummy functions just for the purposes of this demonstration.

00:07:10.700 --> 00:07:14.739
But I'm going to show you how easy it is to get the testing infrastructure set up here.

00:07:14.739 --> 00:07:16.660
So here's my package over here.

00:07:16.660 --> 00:07:20.540
Looks pretty similar to what you used before.

00:07:20.540 --> 00:07:21.540
You've seen before.

00:07:21.940 --> 00:07:25.820
So I've already loaded my libraries, I've already installed use this and test that.

00:07:25.820 --> 00:07:29.820
So I'm going to run use test that function here.

00:07:29.820 --> 00:07:34.100
And you'll see here that it created a brand new test directory down here.

00:07:34.100 --> 00:07:36.859
Within that is the test that directory.

00:07:36.859 --> 00:07:39.179
And this is where most of your tests are going to live.

00:07:39.179 --> 00:07:47.380
To create the very first one, I'm going to do the use test.

00:07:47.380 --> 00:07:48.380
And I'm actually not going to do add.

00:07:48.380 --> 00:07:49.899
It actually doesn't matter what I pick.

00:07:49.899 --> 00:07:53.739
I'm going to pick the add things set of functions.

00:07:53.739 --> 00:07:56.820
And what it's done there, if I go back into the test that, it's already created this R

00:07:56.820 --> 00:07:59.339
file for me and opened it up for me with some dummy text.

00:07:59.339 --> 00:08:01.220
Again, this is very simple.

00:08:01.220 --> 00:08:03.500
You're going to want to change this, obviously.

00:08:03.500 --> 00:08:05.179
Nobody cares about two times two.

00:08:05.179 --> 00:08:06.859
You don't really need to prove that.

00:08:06.859 --> 00:08:13.100
But that's just how easy it is to get going.

00:08:13.100 --> 00:08:14.339
So I'll give you an example here.

00:08:14.339 --> 00:08:18.700
This is from the string R package and this is taken straight out of Hadley's book.

00:08:19.260 --> 00:08:21.500
This will give you an idea of what your tests are going to look like.

00:08:21.500 --> 00:08:25.299
At the top, you have a context, which is a description of the test that you're running

00:08:25.299 --> 00:08:26.299
here.

00:08:26.299 --> 00:08:31.980
And then you have each of these little sections here, the test that is the test itself.

00:08:31.980 --> 00:08:36.260
It's exercising the output of a single function with one or more expectations.

00:08:36.260 --> 00:08:39.979
And the expectations themselves describe the expected result of a computation.

00:08:39.979 --> 00:08:41.659
You can have multiple of them.

00:08:41.659 --> 00:08:43.820
Here you see they're all using expect equal.

00:08:43.820 --> 00:08:47.580
But if you look at the documentation for test that, you have a lot of different choices.

00:08:47.580 --> 00:08:48.979
You can test for a known error.

00:08:48.979 --> 00:08:50.500
You can test for matching.

00:08:50.500 --> 00:08:54.780
You can test for all kinds of things using these functions.

00:08:54.780 --> 00:08:56.900
So I'm going to go back over into the code.

00:08:56.900 --> 00:09:01.179
And here, this is basically that same dummy package that I've been working with.

00:09:01.179 --> 00:09:03.380
But I've already created tests here.

00:09:03.380 --> 00:09:08.780
So you'll see in my R package, I've got three different related sets of functions.

00:09:08.780 --> 00:09:13.820
And then I have tests for each of those in the test that subdirectory here.

00:09:13.820 --> 00:09:21.219
What I'm going to be looking at here is the Uniqueify function, which takes a character

00:09:21.219 --> 00:09:23.020
vector and spits out the unique values.

00:09:23.020 --> 00:09:25.960
It's not very interesting, but it's pretty good for a demo.

00:09:25.960 --> 00:09:29.580
And then there's some related tests that I've already written over here.

00:09:29.580 --> 00:09:35.020
So to run these, if you're in RStudio, you can do command or control shift T. It'll run

00:09:35.020 --> 00:09:37.020
all the tests in a package.

00:09:37.020 --> 00:09:40.099
And you'll see the output over here in the build.

00:09:40.099 --> 00:09:41.099
Can you read that okay?

00:09:41.099 --> 00:09:43.539
Let me see if I can make that bigger.

00:09:43.539 --> 00:09:45.859
Over here in the build, it'll give you the output of that.

00:09:45.859 --> 00:09:49.619
You'll see that it's just running DevTools tests under the hood.

00:09:49.619 --> 00:09:52.260
And over here in the output, you'll see the different contexts that it ran.

00:09:52.260 --> 00:09:55.940
Those are the contexts that you have at the top of your test file.

00:09:55.940 --> 00:09:58.820
And then you'll get some feedback on whether they passed or failed.

00:09:58.820 --> 00:09:59.979
And these all passed.

00:09:59.979 --> 00:10:00.979
That's great.

00:10:00.979 --> 00:10:05.739
So at this point, I'm going to make a change to my code.

00:10:05.739 --> 00:10:09.419
Right now I'm only expecting a character vector, but I want to be able to handle factors as

00:10:09.419 --> 00:10:10.419
well.

00:10:10.419 --> 00:10:14.380
So I'm going to add some very simple code to be able to handle factors.

00:10:14.380 --> 00:10:15.380
This is great.

00:10:15.380 --> 00:10:16.380
I'm going to save it.

00:10:16.380 --> 00:10:19.260
I'm going to run the test, because I just do this as a habit, just to make sure everything's

00:10:19.260 --> 00:10:21.020
still working.

00:10:21.020 --> 00:10:25.219
And it did not like that.

00:10:25.219 --> 00:10:26.219
What did I do?

00:10:26.219 --> 00:10:28.219
Oh, did I?

00:10:28.219 --> 00:10:31.219
That was really smart of me, wasn't it?

00:10:31.219 --> 00:10:32.219
All right.

00:10:32.219 --> 00:10:33.219
Thank you.

00:10:33.219 --> 00:10:41.059
Let's try that again.

00:10:41.059 --> 00:10:42.059
Thank you.

00:10:42.059 --> 00:10:44.979
And in this case, you're going to see that one of my tests failed.

00:10:44.979 --> 00:10:49.859
So over here you still have the context over here in the output, but you'll see that one

00:10:49.859 --> 00:10:50.859
of them have failed.

00:10:50.859 --> 00:10:51.859
And it tells me why.

00:10:51.859 --> 00:10:54.780
It says Uniqueify does not handle factors.

00:10:54.780 --> 00:11:00.299
That's the benefit of having a really descriptive name here in your test.

00:11:00.380 --> 00:11:03.780
I can now go looking for that and it says, oh, well, I had a test.

00:11:03.780 --> 00:11:07.500
Because it didn't use to handle factors, I was proving that it didn't use to handle factors.

00:11:07.500 --> 00:11:08.500
In this case, it does now.

00:11:08.500 --> 00:11:12.659
So I need to change up my test.

00:11:12.659 --> 00:11:15.140
Now I am going to expect it to handle factors.

00:11:15.140 --> 00:11:17.619
I'm going to run the test again.

00:11:17.619 --> 00:11:18.619
Life is good.

00:11:18.619 --> 00:11:23.299
They're all passing now.

00:11:23.299 --> 00:11:27.219
So once you have this set up, this is a really simple development workflow.

00:11:27.219 --> 00:11:29.880
You modify your code to your tests.

00:11:29.880 --> 00:11:35.119
You test the packages with command shift T or devtools test and you repeat until all

00:11:35.119 --> 00:11:41.479
the tests pass.

00:11:41.479 --> 00:11:45.840
So as you're designing these tests, you're going to want to put yourself into the shoes

00:11:45.840 --> 00:11:48.799
of the user, the consumer of each function.

00:11:48.799 --> 00:11:50.919
What would you expect to happen?

00:11:50.919 --> 00:11:55.280
What are some common mistakes or typos that you might anticipate that a user will put

00:11:55.280 --> 00:11:56.280
in there for you?

00:11:56.280 --> 00:12:02.320
You're going to want to focus on your external interfaces, your input types, and integration

00:12:02.320 --> 00:12:06.000
points since those are the areas that tend to be most fragile.

00:12:06.000 --> 00:12:10.440
Write one test for each behavior so that you always know where to find the test for a given

00:12:10.440 --> 00:12:11.440
behavior.

00:12:11.440 --> 00:12:15.400
And when you discover bugs, write tests for those as well so you're notified if they crop

00:12:15.400 --> 00:12:17.960
up again later.

00:12:17.960 --> 00:12:20.919
As you're writing these tests, you may find that parts of the functional code would be

00:12:20.919 --> 00:12:23.599
a little easier to test if they were more isolated.

00:12:23.599 --> 00:12:27.359
We'll come back to that later in the talk, but generally speaking, if some area of the

00:12:27.359 --> 00:12:32.200
code is hard to test, it's also going to be hard to maintain.

00:12:32.200 --> 00:12:36.080
But before we get to that, let's take a look at some Shiny applications.

00:12:36.080 --> 00:12:39.359
Joe talked about this a little bit this morning and Winston did a really nice talk on this

00:12:39.359 --> 00:12:42.880
last year, so I'm not going to get too deeply into this, but I wanted to give you a quick

00:12:42.880 --> 00:12:44.640
idea of how this works.

00:12:44.640 --> 00:12:46.919
This is also really easy to set up.

00:12:46.919 --> 00:12:49.400
It's also three steps just like test that.

00:12:49.400 --> 00:12:51.239
But Shiny test works a little bit differently.

00:12:51.239 --> 00:12:58.559
It compares the state of the application to a previously expected state of the application.

00:12:58.559 --> 00:13:02.799
Shiny apps, because they're interactive, are a little more difficult to test straightforwardly.

00:13:02.799 --> 00:13:08.719
So this is a� I can't remember what he called it, but you're comparing the state of the

00:13:08.719 --> 00:13:12.479
application for the way you expect it to the state of the application where it's working

00:13:12.479 --> 00:13:13.479
right now.

00:13:13.479 --> 00:13:17.400
It's kind of a snapshot-based testing strategy.

00:13:17.400 --> 00:13:18.880
So easy to set up.

00:13:18.880 --> 00:13:20.760
There's basically three different things to do.

00:13:21.280 --> 00:13:25.719
You want to install your libraries, you want to record your test or take that initial snapshot,

00:13:25.719 --> 00:13:29.659
and then later on you run the test app function to test it and then compare it against your

00:13:29.659 --> 00:13:31.679
previous snapshot.

00:13:31.679 --> 00:13:33.919
First you start by running record test.

00:13:33.919 --> 00:13:38.760
This will open up an interface where you have your target app on the left and a recorder

00:13:38.760 --> 00:13:41.119
app on the right.

00:13:41.119 --> 00:13:45.760
And what you would do is over in your target app, this is number one in the slide here,

00:13:45.760 --> 00:13:50.840
you make changes to your application, you do controls, you act as if you were a user.

00:13:50.840 --> 00:13:54.119
And then over in number two over here in your recorder app, you'll notice that it's recording

00:13:54.119 --> 00:13:55.799
everything you do.

00:13:55.799 --> 00:14:00.099
At some point you take a snapshot, which is number three up here, then you give it a name

00:14:00.099 --> 00:14:01.880
and save it, which is number four there.

00:14:01.880 --> 00:14:07.799
So you're basically recording what a user would do and setting up that state.

00:14:07.799 --> 00:14:13.200
Then once you record it and save it, it's going to open up the file for you.

00:14:13.200 --> 00:14:16.159
You can edit it if you want to, you can change it up.

00:14:16.159 --> 00:14:17.479
In this case we're not going to do that.

00:14:17.479 --> 00:14:22.479
We're going to move on and we're going to run test app now and you're going to run that

00:14:22.479 --> 00:14:28.679
same app and it's going to play back those things that you recorded earlier.

00:14:28.679 --> 00:14:35.119
If everything's the same, it'll just say pass, but if it's different, it gives you the option

00:14:35.119 --> 00:14:36.919
to take a look at why.

00:14:36.919 --> 00:14:42.679
So when you hit why, you can take a look at the JSON encapsulation of that state, which

00:14:42.679 --> 00:14:43.679
is number one here.

00:14:43.679 --> 00:14:46.000
And you can also look at some screenshots.

00:14:46.000 --> 00:14:47.000
Number two here.

00:14:47.000 --> 00:14:50.320
Again, I'm not getting into this because it's online and Joe talked about it a little bit

00:14:50.320 --> 00:14:55.400
this morning, but you can toggle back and forth and see what the differences are.

00:14:55.400 --> 00:14:59.039
If you're okay with the differences or you've made some changes and the updated version

00:14:59.039 --> 00:15:03.599
is what you want, number three here you can update and quit or you can just pick quit

00:15:03.599 --> 00:15:08.080
and then investigate why it might have gone wrong if it's not what you expected.

00:15:08.080 --> 00:15:12.599
So getting back to something I alluded to earlier, designing for your ease of testing

00:15:12.599 --> 00:15:16.280
is also designing for ease of maintenance and so there's some good software practices

00:15:16.280 --> 00:15:17.280
involved here.

00:15:17.280 --> 00:15:18.520
So let's talk about that quickly.

00:15:18.520 --> 00:15:24.000
Again, your goals are reliability, reproducibility, flexibility, longevity and scalability.

00:15:24.000 --> 00:15:27.239
You want a good user experience and you want a high degree of confidence that everything

00:15:27.239 --> 00:15:30.000
you're doing and all of your changes aren't going to break what you've already done well

00:15:30.000 --> 00:15:31.000
before.

00:15:31.000 --> 00:15:35.320
You also want to take a look at a modular design for ease of testing and maintenance.

00:15:35.320 --> 00:15:36.359
Break things down.

00:15:36.359 --> 00:15:41.159
It's much easier to test a small function than it is to test a huge function because

00:15:41.159 --> 00:15:44.119
it's much more easy to control the inputs and outputs that way.

00:15:44.119 --> 00:15:48.840
You want to decouple your code, pull out helper functions, things like that to make it easier

00:15:48.840 --> 00:15:50.679
to maintain later.

00:15:50.679 --> 00:15:52.179
Don't repeat yourself.

00:15:52.179 --> 00:15:53.840
Keep it simple if you can.

00:15:53.840 --> 00:15:57.760
So I don't mean keep your analysis simple, I mean keep the pieces of your analysis, your

00:15:57.760 --> 00:16:02.960
pieces of code as simple as possible, again, so they're isolated and easy to test and maintain.

00:16:02.960 --> 00:16:06.080
And you want a consistent coding style so that it makes it easier for future you to

00:16:06.080 --> 00:16:09.159
read or for your colleagues for that matter.

00:16:09.159 --> 00:16:13.039
Then on the shiny test side of things, for example, you want your ease of use user experience

00:16:13.039 --> 00:16:17.919
tested, the state of that application when you've done a certain set of user actions,

00:16:17.919 --> 00:16:22.719
you want that to be as consistent as possible and you can prove that with some shiny tests.

00:16:22.719 --> 00:16:24.900
And finally, you want to make sure that your error handling is good.

00:16:24.900 --> 00:16:28.239
You want to make sure if something does go wrong, that the message you give your user

00:16:28.239 --> 00:16:31.039
is actionable.

00:16:31.039 --> 00:16:33.520
So at that point, yay, profit.

00:16:33.520 --> 00:16:37.080
However, you have to remember that the actual tests themselves are not going to ensure the

00:16:37.080 --> 00:16:40.840
high quality of your script or application, they just verify it when it's there.

00:16:40.840 --> 00:16:45.640
You need to develop a workflow of adding these tests as you go along to ensure that you're

00:16:45.640 --> 00:16:49.320
actually building in the good code in the first place.

00:16:49.320 --> 00:16:51.520
So I'm going to close up here with some resources.

00:16:51.520 --> 00:16:54.039
There's some really good things you can read or watch.

00:16:54.039 --> 00:16:58.400
There is the R packages and advanced R books by Hadley Wickham are an excellent place to

00:16:58.400 --> 00:17:03.679
start, not only for testing, but also for good software design in general.

00:17:03.679 --> 00:17:06.560
And I wanted to add to that as well, it is never too late to start.

00:17:06.560 --> 00:17:10.520
If you've got a big package and you're, like, intimidated by it, I've certainly inherited

00:17:10.520 --> 00:17:14.000
packages that I'm intimidated by, just start small.

00:17:14.000 --> 00:17:17.560
Start small, add something in, follow Hadley's advice, it's really good advice, it's not

00:17:17.560 --> 00:17:20.439
hard to get started, it's three steps.

00:17:20.439 --> 00:17:24.280
There's also this Charles Gray blog post on test that auto test.

00:17:24.280 --> 00:17:29.280
I don't have time to talk about it, but you can basically turn on auto test and every

00:17:29.280 --> 00:17:31.839
time you save your file, it will run your test for you.

00:17:31.839 --> 00:17:37.680
It's immediate feedback and it's a really cool way to do stuff if you have enough tests

00:17:37.680 --> 00:17:39.300
to make it worth your while.

00:17:39.300 --> 00:17:42.640
And finally, again, I'm going to refer to Winston Chang's talk on shiny tests he did

00:17:42.640 --> 00:17:43.640
last year.

00:17:43.640 --> 00:17:47.540
It's an excellent video if you have a chance to watch that.

00:17:47.540 --> 00:17:51.880
Resources for testing packages, I didn't talk about most of these, I just didn't have time.

00:17:51.880 --> 00:17:55.680
But all of these pink words are actually links.

00:17:55.680 --> 00:17:59.560
So if you want to pull down my slides at the end of the conference, you can go through

00:17:59.560 --> 00:18:05.520
these are really excellently documented, and so you can read all about them there as well.

00:18:05.520 --> 00:18:07.400
Next steps, start small, give it a go.

00:18:07.400 --> 00:18:09.979
There's no reason not to do this, it's three steps.

00:18:09.979 --> 00:18:12.520
You don't have to do everything in the world right at the very beginning.

00:18:12.520 --> 00:18:15.880
You can start with your major functions and move on from there.

00:18:15.880 --> 00:18:20.680
Look for opportunities to improve the functional code to be more testable and therefore maintainable.

00:18:20.680 --> 00:18:24.760
My future self will thank you, trust me, I've been there.

00:18:24.760 --> 00:18:31.000
If you are using source control, check in your tests as well as your functional code.

00:18:31.000 --> 00:18:34.400
So that it always stays in sync with what you're actually building.

00:18:34.400 --> 00:18:40.359
And if you have a continuous integration system like Jenkins or Travis, if you check it in

00:18:40.359 --> 00:18:47.079
with your code, there's pretty easy ways to plug it in and have it run the tests for you

00:18:47.160 --> 00:18:52.599
as part of your regular build integration system for your packages.

00:18:52.599 --> 00:18:56.079
And then you can bask in the warm glow of reliability and maintainability because your

00:18:56.079 --> 00:18:59.199
tests are telling you whether or not you've broken something and you don't have to guess

00:18:59.199 --> 00:19:02.280
and you don't have to wait for your users to find it.

00:19:02.280 --> 00:19:03.280
Thank you very much.

00:19:03.280 --> 00:19:06.880
If you want to have any questions about this or anything else, feel free to email me.

00:19:06.880 --> 00:19:09.920
I'll be around in the Pro Lounge as well later.

00:19:09.920 --> 00:19:12.959
And slides and code examples will be available after the conference.

00:19:12.959 --> 00:19:13.959
Thank you.

00:19:13.959 --> 00:19:15.839
Bye-bye.

